milestone.title: v0.5.0
milestone.description:
Users should be able to use `turbopelican.toml` to configure their project fully, not just for the present subset of settings that are handled. This configuration can be found from https://docs.getpelican.com/en/latest/settings.html. Also, Turbopelican, when loading configuration, should use a priority ranking for settings in this order:

1. Is the setting set explicitly?
2. If not, is the setting set in an inherited section? (Only applicable to publishconf.py)
3. If not, is there a default setting?

If the answer to all these is no for any given setting, Turbopelican should raise an error.

issue.title: Use string literal instead of `codegen.typescript`
issue.body:
We see string literals for
- Creator (two options)
- Codegen style (two options)

So it becomes an inconsistency that it is a `typescript` boolean, instead of a `language` option

comment.body: I don't believe this to be an inconsistency. Enabling typescript still generates Luau code, but it also generates a definition file, not a source file—so making it seem as if you are choosing between the two would be misleading.

issue.title: Inconsistent Parsing of Large Integer in JSON Respons
issue.body: ### I have checked the following: - [x] I have searched existing issues and found nothing related to my issue. ### This bug is: - [x] making Bruno unusable for me - [ ] slowing me down but I'm able to continue working - [ ] annoying - [ ] this feature was working in a previous version but is broken in the current release. ### Bruno version 2.3.0 ### Operating System macOs 15.5 ### Describe the bug For json response ```json {"id": 54739488869584896} ``` Bruno is parsing as ```json { "id": 54739488869584900 } ``` ### Reproducer Python script that run a simple server at port 8000. ```python from http.server import BaseHTTPRequestHandler, HTTPServer import json class SimpleHandler(BaseHTTPRequestHandler): def do_GET(self): data = {"id": 54739488869584896} response_json = json.dumps(data) self.send_response(200) self.send_header('Content-type', 'application/json') self.end_headers() self.wfile.write(response_json.encode('utf-8')) def run(server_class=HTTPServer, handler_class=SimpleHandler, port=8000): server_address = ('', port) httpd = server_class(server_address, handler_class) print(f"visit : http://localhost:{port}/") try: httpd.serve_forever() except KeyboardInterrupt: print("\nServer stopped.") httpd.server_close() if __name__ == '__main__': run() ``` ```bash curl http://localhost:8000/ ``` is returning correct response. ### .bru file to reproduce the bug _No response_ ### Screenshots/Live demo link Bruno Screenshots curl Screenshots ![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/3767c1cf-870f-49b9-a0e8-1d46e674b18e) https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/e428fc5c-c25e-40ea-8149-422c209abaff

comment.body: Interesting... All I did was spin up a node env in my terminal.. typed in the input and it spat back out the incorrect number: Looks like the Number is too big for JavaScript? I found a StackOverflow with a discussion to a similar issue: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/307179/what-is-javascripts-highest-integer-value-that-a-number-can-go-to-without-losin Quick fix here might be to return it as a string instead?
